{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600117"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:01:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:01:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15606"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15606"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.1,0.35,0.4,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8297"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70394"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8297"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15606"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55858"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7005"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20027"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20029"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20032"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70394"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA histological section from a thyroid nodule shows well-differentiated follicular cells arranged in microfollicles. There is evidence of capsular invasion, but nuclear features are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis for this thyroid lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anaplastic thyroid carcinoma","Medullary thyroid carcinoma","Follicular thyroid carcinoma","Follicular thyroid adenoma","Papillary thyroid carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological findings are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Efollicular thyroid carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, showing well-differentiated follicular cells arranged in microfollicles with capsular invasion. The absence of distinctive nuclear features helps distinguish it from other thyroid malignancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key features of other thyroid lesions are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaplastic thyroid carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows marked cellular pleomorphism, numerous mitoses and giant cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedullary thyroid carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows sheets of polygonal to spindle cells with amyloid deposits\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollicular thyroid adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E appears similar but lacks capsular or vascular invasion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPapillary thyroid carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows characteristic ground glass nuclei, nuclear grooves and pseudoinclusions\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of capsular invasion is the key distinguishing feature between follicular carcinoma and adenoma, as both show well-differentiated follicular cells arranged in microfollicles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Follicular thyroid carcinoma shows well-differentiated follicular cells arranged in microfollicles with capsular and/or vascular invasion.","Capsular or vascular invasion is required to distinguish follicular thyroid carcinoma from follicular adenoma.","The key histological features of thyroid carcinomas include cellular arrangement, nuclear characteristics, and presence of invasion."],"references":["\u0022Follicular thyroid carcinoma - alt -- high mag\u0022 by Nephron is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Follicular_thyroid_carcinoma_-_alt_--_high_mag.jpg","Shah JP. Thyroid carcinoma: epidemiology, histology, and diagnosis. Clin Adv Hematol Oncol. 2015 Apr;13(4 Suppl 4):3-6. PMID: 26430868; PMCID: PMC5526593","Kitahara CM, Schneider AB. Epidemiology of Thyroid Cancer. Cancer Epidemiol Biomarkers Prev. 2022 Jul 1;31(7):1284-1297. doi: 10.1158/1055-9965.EPI-21-1440. PMID: 35775227; PMCID: PMC9473679","Boucai L, Zafereo M, Cabanillas ME. Thyroid Cancer: A Review. JAMA. 2024 Feb 6;331(5):425-435. doi: 10.1001/jama.2023.26348. PMID: 38319329","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55858"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15606"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21174"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21174"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1Ega6k3XYjV9ECgGOHAmDpMcq6h9kH.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1Ega6k3XYjV9ECgGOHAmDpMcq6h9kH.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":1200}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55858"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T20:46:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T20:51:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8297"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70394"}}},"meta":{